n in the work of writers originally from different geographical areas of transatlantic encounter, such as Europe, Latin America, North America, and the Caribbean.After Translation examines from a transnational perspective the various ways in which translation facilitates the circulation of modern poetry and poetics across the Atlantic. It rethinks the theoretical paradigm of Anglo-American "modernism" based on the transnational, interlingual, and transhistorical features of the work of key modern poets writing on both sides of the Atlantic- namely, the Portuguese Fernando Pessoa; the Chilean Vicente Huidobro; the Spaniard Federico Garcia Lorca; the San Francisco-based poets Jack Spicer, Robert Duncan, and Robin Blaser; the Barbadian Kamau Brathwaite; and the Brazilian brothers Haroldo and Augusto de Campos.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAmerican poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature) 0aPoeticsxHistoryy20th century. 0aPoetryxTranslating. 0aSpanish American poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aTransnationalism in literature. 4aavant-garde. 4acultural circulation. 4aliterary history. 4amodern poetry. 4amodernism. 4amultilingualism. 4apoetics. 4apostcolonialism. 4atransatlantic literature. 4atranslation. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823252145zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823252145423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823252145.jpg  a978-3-11-070729-8  FUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  a